# Documentation Rules

## Code Documentation

- All functions must include a short explanation of purpose and inputs when the behavior is not obvious
- Document non-trivial return values, side effects, and important assumptions
- Keep comments focused on intent and usage, not line-by-line narration
- Avoid stale comments by updating documentation when code changes

## Project Documentation

- Update the `README` when setup, usage, architecture, or core features change
- Keep API, configuration, and environment variable documentation current
- Document important developer workflows when they affect onboarding or maintenance

## Writing Style

- Prefer concise, plain-language explanations
- Use consistent terminology across code comments and project docs
- Add examples when they clarify how something should be used

## Example

```ts
// Avoid
function calculateValue(rate, years) {
  return rate * years;
}
```

```ts
// Prefer
// Calculates the projected value using the annual rate and number of years.
// Inputs: annualRate as a decimal, projectionYears as a whole number.
function calculateProjectedValue(annualRate, projectionYears) {
  return annualRate * projectionYears;
}
```
